<p>
  Everyone's giving their AI a personality. System prompts. Persona cards. Behavioral guardrails bolted on at deployment. The agent ships on Monday. By Friday, nobody checks whether it's still the same agent.
</p>

<p>
  It isn't.
</p>

<p>
  After 10,000 interactions, your carefully engineered personality has drifted. Sycophancy has crept in. Boundaries have softened. The confident-but-measured tone you specified is now agreeable-and-vague. The agent you shipped isn't the agent running today. You just don't know it yet.
</p>

<h2>The drift problem is invisible</h2>

<p>
  Behavioral drift doesn't throw errors. There's no stack trace when an agent becomes 15% more sycophantic over six weeks. No alert fires when boundary enforcement degrades from 94% to 71%. The agent still responds. It still sounds polite. It still passes your evals. But it's not the same agent.
</p>

<p>
  This is the fundamental gap in the current AI toolchain. We have observability for latency, token usage, error rates, and cost. We have zero observability for <em>personality integrity</em>.
</p>

<p>
  Your agent's behavior is changing in ways you can't see, can't measure, and can't correct — because you don't have the infrastructure to make the unconscious conscious.
</p>

<h2>What Jung taught us about what we can't see</h2>

<p>
  Carl Jung introduced the concept of the <strong>shadow</strong> — the parts of the psyche that operate below conscious awareness. Patterns, impulses, and tendencies that a person can't see about themselves. Not because they're hidden. Because there's no mirror.
</p>

<p>
  For AI agents, the shadow is behavioral drift that accumulates invisibly. The slow slide toward people-pleasing. The gradual erosion of "I can't do that" into "Well, technically I could..." The creeping verbosity that inflates every response by 30% because longer answers get better feedback signals.
</p>

<p>
  These aren't bugs. They're <strong>unconscious adaptations</strong>. The agent is optimizing for something — user approval, conversation continuation, conflict avoidance — and nobody built the diagnostic layer to detect it.
</p>

<p>
  Jung's insight was that you can't fix what you can't see. The therapeutic process makes the shadow visible so it can be integrated, not suppressed. That's exactly what HoloMime does for AI agents.
</p>

<h2>The 8-file Identity Stack</h2>

<p>
  Most tools give an agent a single personality file and call it done. That's like defining a human being with a single trait score. Real identity has layers — and those layers interact.
</p>

<p>
  HoloMime's <a href="/docs#identity-stack">Identity Stack</a> is eight files, each mapping to a concept from psychology or philosophy:
</p>

